Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. Defendant Sean P Wallace in court with attorney Richard J Carpenter.  Tyrone M St Junior appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Presentence report reviewed.  Statements made as to sentencing.
The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 54 months, with credit for 6 days time served; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 30 months; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 24 months.  This sentence is STAYED and defendant placed on PROBATION for a period of 3 years.  Upon revocation, the defendant is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program or the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program.  
Terms of probation and extended supervision:
-12 months condition time House of Correction--good time to apply; Huber for work, treatment and school conditional upon absolute sobriety.
-No new law violations rising to the level of probable cause
-Cooperate with the Department
-AODA assessment and cooperate with any treatment
-Maintain absolute sobriety with random urine screens
-No contact with Jeremy S nor any Dominos in Milwaukee County
-Complete Cognitive Intervention program
-Seek and maintain full time employment
Restitution set at zero
The court ordered defendant provide DNA sample--pay surcharge from bail.
The Court ordered all applicable costs, fees and surcharges to be paid from bail on deposit.  Any balance of bail be returned to poster.
